  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What are the penalties for money laundering under federal law?",
  "response": "Under federal law in the United States, money laundering is a serious offense with significant penalties. The specific penalties can vary depending on the circumstances of the case, but generally include the following:\n\n1. **Criminal Penalties**:\n   - **Fines**: Individuals convicted of money laundering can face substantial fines. Under the **Money Laundering Control Act** (18 U.S.C. \u00a7 1956), the maximum fine can be up to **$500,000 or twice the value of the laundered funds, whichever is greater**.\n   - **Imprisonment**: Convicted individuals can face significant prison sentences. For a single money laundering offense, the maximum prison term is **up to 20 years**. If the money laundering is tied to other serious crimes (e.g., drug trafficking, terrorism), the penalties can be even more severe.\n\n2. **Civil Penalties**:\n   - In addition to criminal penalties, individuals and entities may face **civil forfeiture** of assets involved in or derived from the money laundering activity. This means the government can seize property, funds, or other assets connected to the illegal activity.\n\n3. **Enhanced Penalties**:\n   - If the money laundering involves proceeds from certain crimes, such as **drug trafficking** or **terrorism**, the penalties can be enhanced. For example, involvement in money laundering related to a **continuing financial crimes enterprise** (18 U.S.C. \u00a7 225) can result in a **mandatory minimum sentence of 10 years** and fines up to **$10 million for organizations**.\n\n4. **Additional Consequences**:\n   - Conviction for money laundering can lead to other consequences, including **loss of professional licenses**, **ineligibility for government contracts**, and **damage to personal and professional reputations**.\n\n5. **International Context**:\n   - Money laundering cases involving international transactions or foreign entities may trigger additional penalties under laws like the **Foreign Corrupt Practices Act (FCPA)** or **USA PATRIOT Act**, which further expand the scope of liability.\n\n### Key Statutes:\n- **18 U.S.C. \u00a7 1956**: Prohibits money laundering and sets criminal penalties.\n- **18 U.S.C. \u00a7 1957**: Prohibits engaging in monetary transactions with criminally derived property and carries similar penalties.\n\nIf you are facing allegations of money laundering, it is crucial to consult with an experienced attorney to understand the specific legal implications and potential defenses.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
